+### 6. pytest autouse Fixture Mutation (Hermes-specific)
+
+**WHEN a test passes in manual Python but fails under pytest:**
+
+The Hermes `conftest.py` has two `autouse` fixtures that reset state between tests:
+- `_reset_module_state` — clears tool registries, approval state, ContextVars, env vars, module-level dicts
+- `_hermetic_environment` — deletes credential/behavioral env vars, redirects `HERMES_HOME`
+
+These can mutate module-level singletons (frozensets, class attributes, global lookup tables) that your test's code depends on, even when you create fresh instances with `object.__new__()`, because the method under test reads from shared module state.
+
+**Diagnostic:** Add `print()` inside the test to dump suspect values (e.g., `cfg.rollout_platforms`, `os.environ.get('KEY')`) and compare with manual Python. If values differ, check `conftest.py::_reset_module_state` for the mutating fixture.
+
+**Common victims:** `_TERMINAL_OUTPUT_TOOLS`, `HERMES_SESSION_SOURCE` env var, `ToolOutputCompactionConfig` field defaults read from module state, any `getattr(self, ...)` that falls back to module-level lookup.
+
+### Git safety: deleted tracked files
+
+When `git ls-files --deleted` shows tracked files, **stop and restore before proceeding**. This
+happens when files are accidentally removed from the working tree (e.g., by a prior operation
+that didn't complete cleanly). Restoring is a single command:
+
+```bash
+git checkout HEAD -- <file>
+git ls-files --deleted  # verify empty
+```
+
+Do NOT proceed with commits, diffs, or assertions while deleted files exist — the guard check
+`test -z "$(git ls-files --deleted)"` will fail and halt the workflow.
+
